\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator stated that the programme in terms of all the Criteria meet the minimum requirements for accreditation and recommended that the programme should be accredited without conditions.  \line \line With regards to criterion 1\'2C the programme is focused on the development of creative writers in the entertainment media industry. The Institution is well-established and offers programmes in film\'2C television\'2C radio\'2C performance and entrepreneurship-focused in the entertainment sphere. All the programmes have elements of creative writing and this programme is therefore a logical development. The long-term vision of the Institution is to develop multidisciplinary teams that bring their specialist skills. In the modules listed a picture is provided of the combination of compulsory and electives. The evaluator is of the view that all modules identified will contribute to the overall purpose of the programme which is well-designed. The comprehensive module outlines indicate coherence of the programme articulation possibilities are indicated. The evaluator is of the view that the Institution will resource the programme appropriately at all four sites of delivery. \line \line With regards to criterion 2\'2C the Recruitment strategy is outlined. The admission criteria are in line with legislation. No selection criteria are applied barring the enrollment plan. The evaluator does clarity on the enrollment plan figures as it is not clear whether these pertain to all four sites or are per site of delivery. A breakdown of enrollment per site is required. RPL processes are indicated but the evaluator does have a question as to whether the RPL procedure is a deviation from normal RPL processes. The RPL policy document could not be opened and that should be resubmitted. \line \line A list of staff members is provided who would possibly be teaching on this programme. Staff members are suitably qualified and have Masters or doctorates in the relevant fields. At each site a Program Coordinator has been appointed with an overall coordinator for the programme. In addition there is evidence that staff development takes place systemically as per the plans. Staff members listed are mainly full-time and are suitably qualified. The Institution does demonstrate that there are sufficient HR policies to govern all staffing matters that are in line with legislation. \line \line The teaching and learning strategy for this programme is one which is focused on simulated workplace learning by students receiving real-life industry related briefs and pitches to develop projects for publication. The mode of delivery is described as transmission teaching\'2C face-to-face\'2C in groups\'2C followed by tutorials discipline-specific workshops\'2C supervised learning industry by professionals and group work. Student support mechanisms are in place and there is evidence that close monitoring of student performance takes place. The Institution ensures that parity of delivery is achieved through provision of Induction packs\'2C course outlines\'2C module outlines and lesson plans for every lecture\'2C as well as reading packs. The learning policy ensures that the teaching is monitored across all four sites of delivery. The same timetable will be running and lecturers communicate with each other across the sites.  \line \line Assessment is described which is within the framework of the assessment policy\'2C with a Capstone project at the end of the year. Both formative and summative assessment is indicated with both internal and external moderation indicated.  Focus is also on integrated assessment. Staff members are required to attend train the trainer sessions especially focused on assessment.\line \line  Infrastructure is suitable and as no specialist equipment is required for this programme\'2C classroom space is available. Students have access to the library and to the materials. The databases and online sources have been provided. Librarians at all four sites attend training. The Institution has indicated that the IT infrastructure is sufficient to service a new intake of students. Provision is made for the IT requirements for the programme coordinator. At all the sites students have access to both the library and it systems. The Institution has also submitted a plan regarding the upgrade of facilities to be achieved by 2023. \line \line With regards to programme administrative services and the MIS system used\'2C there is a platform that manages students and management information systems. This is deemed to be secure. Issues around security and certification are addressed. While there is little information on the administrative processes what has been provided can be deemed to be in line with the minimum standards. It must be noted that the evaluator required supporting documents. Most of the required documents are attached in the Institutional profile and meet the minimum standards. \line \line The Directorate recommends that the programme be accredited with conditions.\cell \pard 

